Decision Tree .... 

So far, we learned Logistic Regression, a model that works well when the relationship is simple and mostly linear.
But not all problems can be solved with a straight line.
This is where Decision Trees come in.

1. What is a Decision Tree?

A Decision Tree is like a flowchart made of yes/no questions.
At each step, the model asks a question about the data and splits it into smaller groups.
Think of it as step-by-step reasoning, just like humans do.

2. Why Not Just Use Logistic Regression?

Logistic Regression draws a straight line (boundary) to separate classes.
But some problems need branching rules instead of a single line.

Example: Predict if a student will Pass/Fail.

If they studied less than 3 hours → Fail.
If they studied more than 3 hours → Next check:
Did they sleep at least 6 hours?
Yes → Pass
No → Fail
Here, Logistic Regression would struggle (since the rule is not a simple straight line).
A Decision Tree handles it naturally.

3. Decision Trees in Action

Example (Student Pass/Fail):

image
      Did the student study > 3 hours?
               /         \
             No           Yes
            Fail     Did they sleep > 6 hours?
                            /       \
                          No         Yes
                        Fail         Pass

Each question = a split.
Each leaf node = final prediction (Pass/Fail).

